🔑 DSA Pattern / Concept
Pattern: Monotonic Stack (decreasing stack)

Why?

For each day, you want to know the next hotter day.

That’s a Next Greater Element problem.

A stack helps track indices of days whose warmer day hasn’t been found yet.

As soon as you see a hotter temperature, you pop from the stack and fill the answer.

✅ Algorithm
Initialize an array ans of size n with all zeros.

Use a stack to store indices of days.

Traverse temperatures from left to right:

While stack not empty and current temperature > temperature at stack top:

Pop index j from stack.

Answer for day j = i - j (distance to warmer day).

Push current index i onto stack.

Remaining indices in stack have no warmer day → answer stays 0.

📌 Full C++ Code
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        int n; cin >> n;
        vector<int> temp(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> temp[i];

        vector<int> ans(n, 0);
        stack<int> st; // stores indices

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            while (!st.empty() && temp[i] > temp[st.top()]) {
                int j = st.top(); st.pop();
                ans[j] = i - j;
            }
            st.push(i);
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cout << ans[i] << " ";
        cout << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
🧮 Dry Run (Sample Input)
Code
temps = [73,74,75,71,69,72,76,73]
Day 0 (73) → next hotter at day 1 → wait 1.

Day 1 (74) → next hotter at day 2 → wait 1.

Day 2 (75) → next hotter at day 6 → wait 4.

Day 3 (71) → next hotter at day 5 → wait 2.

Day 4 (69) → next hotter at day 5 → wait 1.

Day 5 (72) → next hotter at day 6 → wait 1.

Day 6 (76) → no hotter → 0.

Day 7 (73) → no hotter → 0.
Output: 1 1 4 2 1 1 0 0 ✅

🎯 Revision Hook
When revising:

“Daily Temperatures” → Next Greater Element → Monotonic Stack.

Push indices, pop when you find a hotter day, fill distance.

👉 Memory trick:
“Stack stores waiting days, pop when heat arrives.”
